s; did not recover; returned to Berlin."}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST054","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1809-1813","institution_blurb":"Graduated Middlebury College Class of 1812."}],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["minister","clergy","author"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"death","header":"Pastor in South Carolina sent home to die","body":"Poor health led Rev. Perrin to accept a three-year pastorate in South Carolina, hoping a warmer climate would restore him. He did not recover and returned to Berlin Vermont, where he died in February 1824 at age thirty-one."},{"number":2,"category":"literature","header":"Wrote two volumes of poetry before age thirty-one","body":"Rev. Perrin published two volumes of poetry as a Congregational minister preaching in Vermont, New York, and Pennsylvania. A third volume titled Eloida is rumored but no extant copy has been found."},{"number":3,"category":"death","header":"Brandy prescribed as medicine became fatal addiction","body":"Per the 1888 Berlin Vermont history, Rev. Perrin's attending physician prescribed brandy as a medical treatment for the ill health that drove him from his South Carolina pastorate back to Berlin. The prescription created an addiction that the source frankly attributes as the cause of his death at thirty-one."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"short":"Talcott 1876","page":"Entry 1396"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"william-perrin-1792"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}